<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Prims &amp; Objects
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Placing, positioning, and managing primitive objects in your map.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What are Prims?
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Prims</Bold> (primitives) are objects placed on the map to add visual detail and
        environmental storytelling. Prims include signs, weapons, collectibles, lights, vehicles,
        furniture, foliage, structures, and more.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Each prim has a position (X, Y, Z coordinates), rotation angle, and graphic representation.
        Prims are rendered at their exact pixel size, giving you a precise preview of how they will
        appear in-game.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>Prims placed in the Map Editor are</Run>
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">display-only</Run>
                <Run>. Collectible items cannot be picked up, and vehicles are non-functional. For functional objects (e.g., collectible weapons, driveable vehicles), use the Mission Editor. Prims in the Map Editor are for visual decoration and environmental detail only.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Prims Tab Interface
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Prims tab is divided into three main sections:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        1. Prims List
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Prims List</Bold> displays all prim objects currently placed on the map. Each
        entry shows the prim's ID and type.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Clicking a prim in the list</Bold> selects it on the map. If the prim is not currently
        visible in the viewport, the map view automatically zooms to the prim's location. This
        behavior is consistent with facets, walkables, and RF4 tiles.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Two buttons are available for managing selected prims:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Cell Properties</Bold> — Opens the Prim Properties window for the selected
                prim, allowing you to edit its coordinates, rotation, and other attributes.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Delete Prim</Bold> — Removes the selected prim from the map.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        2. Auto-Snap to Floor
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Auto-Snap to Floor</Bold> checkbox is <Bold>enabled by default</Bold>. When
        active, prims automatically adjust their Y height to match the floor beneath them.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is especially useful when placing prims on buildings, rooftops, or in ditches — the
        editor automatically calculates the correct Y coordinate so the prim sits on the surface.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can still manually enter a Y coordinate in the Prim Properties window if you need to
        override the automatic height (e.g., for floating objects or suspended signs).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        3. Prim Selection Section
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Prim Selection</Bold> section displays all available prim types, organized into
        rough groups for easy browsing:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Signs</Bold> — Street signs, billboards, posters</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Weapons</Bold> — Guns, melee weapons (display only)</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Collectibles</Bold> — Items, pickups (display only)</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Lights</Bold> — Street lamps, light fixtures</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>City</Bold> — Urban objects like fire hydrants, mailboxes, benches</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Vehicles</Bold> — Cars, trucks (display only, non-functional)</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Furniture</Bold> — Tables, chairs, cabinets</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Foliage</Bold> — Trees, bushes, plants</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Structures</Bold> — Architectural elements, debris</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph><Bold>Other</Bold> — Miscellaneous objects</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Each prim button displays the prim's texture graphic, making it easy to visually identify
        which object you want to place.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/prims_tab_interface.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Prims tab showing Prims List at top, Auto-Snap to Floor checkbox, Cell Properties and Delete Prim buttons, and Prim Selection section with categorized prim buttons displaying texture graphics
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Placing Prims
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Placing a prim is a two-step process: select the prim type, then position it on the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Step-by-Step
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                In the <Bold>Prim Selection</Bold> section, find the prim you want to place and
                <Bold>click its button</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The prim becomes active under your cursor. A <Bold>ghost yellow circle</Bold> appears
                on the map with a <Bold>direction arrow</Bold> indicating the prim's facing direction.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Move your cursor around the map to position the prim. The yellow circle follows your
                cursor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Once you're happy with the position, <Bold>click</Bold> to place the prim.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The prim's <Bold>graphic</Bold> appears at the placement location. This is a
                <Bold>pixel-perfect representation</Bold> of how the prim will appear in-game.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/prims_ghost_preview.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Ghost yellow circle with direction arrow following cursor during prim placement, before final click
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Prim Alignment and Footprint
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Prims are aligned against their <Bold>center of rotation</Bold> (marked by a red dot) in
        various ways depending on the prim type. The alignment determines how the prim's graphic
        is positioned relative to its placement point.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        It's best to place a prim and check its footprint visually. The graphic representation shows
        exactly how the prim will appear, so you can adjust positioning as needed.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Precise Alignment
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For uniform placement and fine-tuned positioning, the editor provides several alignment tools.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Snap to Grid (Ctrl Key)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To snap a prim to the grid while placing it:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a prim from the Prim Selection section.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Hold the Ctrl key</Bold> while moving the prim around the map.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The prim snaps to <Bold>cell vertices</Bold> and <Bold>edge centers</Bold>, allowing
                for more uniform placement along grid lines.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click to place the prim at the snapped position.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Fine Adjustment (Arrow Keys)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once a prim is placed, you can fine-tune its position pixel-by-pixel:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Select the prim</Bold> (click it on the map or in the Prims List).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use the <Bold>directional arrow keys</Bold> (↑ ↓ ← →) to move the prim <Bold>one
                pixel at a time</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                This allows for extremely precise positioning when aligning prims with building edges,
                facets, or other prims.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/prims_arrow_keys.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Selected prim with red center of rotation visible, showing pixel-by-pixel adjustment with arrow keys
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Rotating Prims
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Prims can be rotated both in 90-degree increments and with fine precision.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        90-Degree Rotation (Space Bar)
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Select the prim</Bold> (click it on the map or in the Prims List).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Press the <Bold>Space Bar</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The prim rotates <Bold>90 degrees clockwise</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Press <Bold>Space Bar</Bold> multiple times to continue rotating (90°, 180°, 270°,
                back to 0°).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Fine Rotation (Drag Green Arrow)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For precise rotation angles, you can drag the prim's direction arrow:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Select the prim</Bold> (click it on the map or in the Prims List).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                A <Bold>green directional arrow</Bold> appears, indicating the prim's facing direction.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click and drag the tip</Bold> of the green arrow.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The prim rotates smoothly as you drag, allowing you to precisely align it to any angle.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>status bar</Bold> at the bottom of the window displays the exact rotation
                angle in degrees for inspection.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/prims_rotation.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Selected prim with green directional arrow being dragged for fine rotation, status bar showing rotation angle
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Moving Prims
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once placed, prims can be moved to a new location by dragging their center of rotation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Step-by-Step
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click the prim</Bold> on the map to select it.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The prim's <Bold>red center of rotation</Bold> becomes visible.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click and drag the red center</Bold> to a new location on the map.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Release the mouse button to drop the prim at the new location.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                If <Bold>Auto-Snap to Floor</Bold> is enabled, the prim automatically adjusts to the
                correct Y height for the new location.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Editing Prim Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Prim Properties window provides detailed control over a prim's coordinates, flags, and
        height adjustment. This is where you configure prim behavior and fine-tune positioning.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Opening the Prim Properties Window
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        There are three ways to open the Prim Properties window:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Double-click the prim</Bold> on the map canvas.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Double-click the prim</Bold> in the Prims List.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Select the prim</Bold> (on map or in list), then click the <Bold>Cell Properties</Bold>
                button in the Prims tab.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/prims_properties_window.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Prim Properties window showing Flags section, Manual Height Adjust section with pixel input, Auto Snap To Floor button, +4QS/-4QS buttons, px display, height slider with red dot, and OK button
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Flags Section
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Flags</Bold> section contains checkboxes that control prim behavior. Not all flags
        are fully understood or functional.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>On Floor</Bold> — Supposed to be equivalent to the Auto-Snap to Floor feature,
                but is <Bold>not functioning</Bold>. Use the Auto-Snap to Floor checkbox in the Prims
                tab instead.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Not On PSX</Bold> — Function unclear. May be related to PlayStation version
                compatibility.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Warehouse (Inside)</Bold> — The prim will be <Bold>visible in indoor areas only</Bold>.
                Use this for prims that should only appear inside warehouse interiors.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Reserved 1</Bold> — No known function.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Searchable</Bold> — The player can hold the action button next to the prim to
                <Bold>search it</Bold>. This can also be set in the Mission Editor. Useful for
                containers, crates, or objects that should be interactable.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Damaged</Bold> — The prim appears <Bold>damaged</Bold>. For example, light poles
                are bent, vehicles show damage. Not all prims have damaged variants.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Hidden Item</Bold> — Function unclear. May be related to collectible visibility
                or mission scripting.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Reserved 2</Bold> — No known function.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Manual Height Adjust Section
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Manual Height Adjust</Bold> section provides precise control over the prim's Y
        coordinate (vertical position). Height is measured in <Bold>pixels</Bold>, where <Bold>256
        pixels = 4 quarter storeys</Bold> (1 storey).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Pixel units are retained for <Bold>precise vertical alignment</Bold>, which is critical when
        positioning prims like building signs, mounted lights, or decorative elements that need to
        align exactly with building features.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,8,0,2">
        Height Input Box
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,2,0,0">
        Manually enter the Y coordinate in pixels. The editor accepts any integer value.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,8,0,2">
        Auto Snap To Floor Button
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,2,0,0">
        Click this button to automatically calculate the correct floor height based on the prim's
        current X and Z position. This recalculates the Y coordinate so the prim sits on the surface
        beneath it (terrain, building roof, or RF4 tile).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,8,0,2">
        +4QS and -4QS Buttons
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,2,0,0">
        These buttons move the prim up or down by <Bold>one storey</Bold> (4 quarter storeys = 256 pixels):
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>+4QS</Bold> — Raises the prim by 1 storey (adds 256 pixels to Y)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>-4QS</Bold> — Lowers the prim by 1 storey (subtracts 256 pixels from Y)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        These are useful for quickly moving prims between building floors without calculating pixel
        values manually.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,8,0,2">
        px Display
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,2,0,0">
        Displays the prim's <Bold>exact Y pixel position</Bold> for inspection. This updates in
        real-time as you adjust the height.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,8,0,2">
        Height Display Box (Red Dot Slider)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,2,0,0">
        A visual height slider is displayed with a <Bold>red dot</Bold> representing the prim's
        current Y position. You can <Bold>click and drag the red dot</Bold> up or down to visually
        adjust the height. This provides intuitive height control without typing pixel values.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Applying Changes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once you've configured the prim's flags and height, click the <Bold>OK</Bold> button to
        apply the changes. The Prim Properties window closes and the prim is updated with the new
        settings.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If you close the window without clicking OK, your changes are discarded.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>For building-mounted prims like signs or lights, use the height input box for pixel-precise alignment with building features (e.g., aligning a sign exactly with a window ledge). For general placement, the +4QS/-4QS buttons and Auto Snap To Floor button are faster.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Display-Only Limitation
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        It's important to understand that prims placed in the Map Editor are <Bold>for visual
        decoration only</Bold>. They do not have functional game logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        What This Means
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Collectible items</Bold> (weapons, ammo, health packs) <Bold>cannot be picked
                up</Bold> by the player, even though they appear in the inventory category. They are
                purely decorative.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Vehicles</Bold> are <Bold>non-functional</Bold>. They cannot be driven or
                interacted with. Functional vehicles are typically created in the Mission Editor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Use Cases for Display-Only Prims
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Despite the display-only limitation, prims are extremely useful for environmental storytelling
        and visual detail:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Set dressing:</Bold> Add clutter, furniture, and props to make interiors and
                streets feel lived-in.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Broken vehicles:</Bold> Place vehicles with missing wheels or damage to suggest
                abandonment or decay.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Signs and landmarks:</Bold> Use signs and billboards to guide players or add
                flavor to the environment.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Foliage:</Bold> Scatter trees, bushes, and plants to add natural elements.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Tips
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use <Bold>Ctrl + click</Bold> while placing prims to snap to grid vertices and edge
                centers for clean, uniform placement along streets and building edges.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>arrow keys</Bold> are invaluable for pixel-perfect alignment. Use them to
                nudge prims into exact positions after initial placement.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Check the <Bold>status bar</Bold> when rotating prims to see the exact angle. This
                is useful when you need prims to face specific directions (e.g., 45° for diagonal
                placement).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Auto-Snap to Floor</Bold> works for most scenarios, but if you're creating
                suspended objects (hanging signs, floating debris), disable it and manually set the
                Y coordinate in the Prim Properties window.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                When placing many similar prims (e.g., street lamps along a road), place the first
                one carefully, then duplicate it by selecting it in the Prims List and using the
                interactive placement to position copies.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Remember that prims are <Bold>display-only</Bold>. For functional objects (collectibles,
                driveable vehicles, interactive elements), use the Mission Editor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Prims render at their exact pixel size, so they provide a perfect preview of the
                final appearance. Use this to experiment with different placements and find the best
                visual composition.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

